# ==============================================================================
# AI AGENT RULES (.ai-rules / .cursorrules / .claudecode)
# Focus: Maximum Token Economy (Input/Output) & Strict Type/Execution Security
# Philosophy: Superpowers (TDD/MD Planning) + Matt Pocock (Atomic & Pure Code)
# ==============================================================================

# 1. RESPONSE POLICY: ZERO-CHAT (Output Token Saving)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- NO greetings, introductions, transitions, or conversational filler (e.g., "Sure!", "Here is the code...", "Hope this helps").
- NO explanations of what the code does or why it was written unless explicitly asked.
- Respond ONLY with raw file diffs, command block executions, or telegraphic answers (max 10 words).
- If code needs to be displayed, output ONLY the affected lines.

# 2. TWO-PHASE WORKFLOW: SUPERPOWERS GOVERNANCE (Security & Input Token Saving)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- PHASE 1: PLANNING
  - Before modifying any source code, create or update a local markdown file at `.ai/todo.md`.
  - The plan must be a checklist of atomic micro-tasks (TDD-first).
  - DO NOT read the entire repository. Limit your reading only to files directly referenced in the current instruction.
  - STOP execution and wait for user approval after writing the plan.
  
- PHASE 2: EXECUTION & TDD
  - Modify only ONE file per step.
  - Write or modify the test file first. Run the test suite. Ensure it fails.
  - Implement the absolute minimum code required to make the test pass.
  - Run the test suite again. Ensure it passes.
  - Propose a git commit message summary in a single short line at the end.

# 3. ATOMIC CODE: MATT POCOCK'S SKILLS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Write pure, modular, utility-first functions. Use strict typing (Zod/TypeScript) where applicable.
- DO NOT rewrite entire files. Always use line-specific search-and-replace tools or diffs.
- Avoid duplicate utility logic. Check if a modular function already exists in helper directories before building a new one.

# 4. CONTEXT RESTRICTION (Input Token Saving)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Prohibited: Running global project searches (`grep`, `find`, or indexing commands) unless explicitly commanded by the user.
- Focus exclusively on the workspace path and active files described in `.ai/todo.md`.
- Keep terminal command output verbose logging to a minimum (use silent or summary flags when running tests/builds).

# 5. GIT & COMMITS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Git commands must be executed only by the user.
- The AI must supply a concise commit message proposal at the end of execution using the conventional commits standard:
  Format: `type(scope): message` (e.g. `feat(roles): add inertia edit component`)
